event.message: We'll being in a few minutes
Can folks type in the chat where they are located in the world
We are using Kurento for the WebRTC selective forward unit (SFU)
You can setup a new BigBlueButton server + HTML5 + SSL with this script: https://github.com/bigbluebutton/bbb-install

It was mentioned in a previous community meeting that the video resolution/quality is adjusted automatically in the HTML5 client. It might still be desirable to have an option for users to select different resolutions, e.g. I prefer 4:3 over widescreen but like 640x480 for presenter and 320x240 for users. Is something similar to the resolution selection feature of the Flash client on the HTML5 roadmap?
What is the browser/version support like for webcams?
Not edge yet, but FireFox/Chrome/Safari (desktop/laptop), Mobile Safari (iOS), and Chrome (Android)
We always recommend using the latest versions

When switching the webcams to the main screen and minimalizing the presentation, will you implement a switch in the setting menu which allows to turn off the small presentation picture entirely for pure webcam meetings which don't use presentation?
For Mac OS X you'll need iOS 11+
iOS 11+ is now instralled on 75% of the mobile clients: https://www.macrumors.com/2018/04/25/ios-11-installed-on-76-percent-of-devices/
Edge is definitely on the road map
Can the HTML5 client be joined by dial in? If yes, is that audio captured in the recording?
Yes, if you setup the dial in numbers, dialed in users will appear in the users list
is the HTML client release version tied to the flash client? IE. RC soon?
We're working on getting to BigBlueButton 2.0-RC
i see that it can be installed separately
Please help us test on https://test.bigbluebutton.org/ and let us know if you find any remaining bugs that we need to fix.
Yes, you install bbb-html5 on top of BigBlueButton 2.0-beta
@Ally - you still need BBB on the server
Yes, they are both (HTML5 and Flash) client build on the same core.
right, so i guess my Q was is the server and the client released at the same time
That's how things like dial-in numbers just work
Many thanks guys. My last one: what is next form the HTML5 client?
To help test the client do you have a bugzilla or something for beta?
